We introduce a typeclass `HasProjectiveDimensionLT X n` expressing that `Ext X Y i` all vanish when `n ‚â§ i`. We study how it behaves with respect to short exact sequences.
When #19591 will be merged, it will possible to show `HasProjectiveDimensionLT X 1 ‚Üî Projective X`.

What are the pros and cons of `HasProjectiveDimensionLT` vs `HasProjectiveDimensionLE`. In other words, swapping the role of `\le` and `<`.

I would say $\mathbb{Z}$ has projective dimension $\le 1$, but of course it is also $< 2$.

Does it matter which one we use in practice? I guess `n = 0` is a boundary case. If that is the reason, please mention it in the docstring.
Thanks for the suggestion. I have added a type class `HasProjectiveDimensionLE X n` as an abbreviation for `HasProjectiveDimensionLT X (n + 1)`, and it seems Lean is able to see through it.
